    "selector": "Frontal Lobe Epilepsy Surgery",
    "selector_info": "Selecting \"Yes\" indicates that the patient underwent frontal lobe epilepsy surgery, a treatment for drug-resistant frontal lobe epilepsy (FLE). According to the study, long-term seizure freedom rates decline over time, with 45% of patients achieving freedom at one year, 34% at two years, and 14% at five years postoperatively. Predictors for better outcomes include early surgical intervention (within two years of epilepsy onset), younger age at surgery, and absence of interictal epileptiform discharges (IEDs) on postoperative EEG at key follow-up intervals. The study analyzed 73 patients, aged 1 to 45 years at surgery, with follow-ups spanning 1 to 16 years. Common histopathological findings included focal cortical dysplasia (47%), gliosis (18%), and neoplastic lesions (26%). Postoperative ",
